"Dubois J.-L.","Selective oxidation of hydrocarbons and the global warming problem",2005,"Catalysis Today","99","1-2",,"5","14",,,10.1016/j.cattod.2004.09.019,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-14644413575&partnerID=40&md5=4bedee3537c3b2041a2dc7cbe66e65ab","ARKEMA, Ctr. De Recherche Rhône-Alpes, Rue Henri Moissan, 69493 Pierre Bénite, France","Dubois, J.-L., ARKEMA, Ctr. De Recherche Rhône-Alpes, Rue Henri Moissan, 69493 Pierre Bénite, France","Based on recently published studies on the life cycle analysis of several chemicals, and the CO2 emissions associated with their production, a new approach to the selective oxidation of light hydrocarbons is discussed. By nature, selective oxidations are also producing CO2 as the end product, much preferred by the thermodynamics. New technologies such as the circulating fluid bed reactor in selective oxidation, could be considered to propose a solution to reduce the CO2 emissions both with respect to the yield improvement, but also as a solution to recover CO2 from a high partial pressure recycling loop. © 2004 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Acrylic acid; CO 2 emissions; Global warming; Process; Propane; Selective oxidation","Acrylics; Carbon dioxide; Carboxylic acids; Catalysts; Chemical reactors; Electrolysis; Global warming; Hydrocarbons; Life cycle; Nuclear energy; Problem solving; Propane; Acrylic acid; CO2 emission; Process; Selective oxidation; Oxidation",,,,,,"Boustead, I., ECO-profiles of the European plastics industry (1996) Climate Change 1995 - Contribution of WG1 to the Second Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , www.apme.org, A report for APME, Brussels, July 2003 and the reference included in it: J.T. Houghton, L.G. Meira Filho, B.A. Callander, N. Harris, A. Kattenberg, K. Maskell (Eds.) Cambridge University Press; Bilans Énergétiques et gaz à Effet de Serre des Filières de Production de Biocarburants en France, p. 2002. , www.ademe.fr, Note de Synthèse, D